# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bran
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bran/abb-grain] ABB traced its origins to the former Australian Barley Board.
[src:bran/abb-grain] Due to the company's expanded operations into different areas, it demutualised to become ABB Grain on 1 July 1999.
[src:bran/abb-grain] In 2004, the company merged with the South Australian storage and handling company AusBulk and United Grower Holdings.
[src:bran/abb-grain] This brought about the control of the two major grain handlers, along with several of AusBulk's divisions.
[src:bran/abb-grain] The company also provided rural services including fertiliser and agrichemical supply and wool and livestock activities.
[src:bran/abb-grain] The latter were supported by the acquisitions of the Adelaide Wool Company, Wardle Co and Stawool in 2007.
[src:bran/abb-grain] ABB had significant operations in New Zealand focused on the trading and distribution of grains and proteins.
[src:bran/abb-grain] In 2007, the company established a joint venture in Ukraine with French malting company Soufflet to accumulate grain, manage supply chain activities and market grain.
[src:bran/abb-grain] In April 2009, Viterra launched a takeover offer.
[src:bran/abb-grain] Combined, the two companies together were responsible for 37 per cent of the world's exports of wheat, canola and barley.
[src:bran/abb-grain] Shareholders approved the merger on 9 September.
[src:bran/abb-grain] ABB was delisted from the Australian Securities Exchange on 25 September 2009.
[src:bran/agronomy] This topic of agronomy involves selective breeding of plants to produce the best crops for various conditions.
[src:bran/agronomy] Plant breeding has increased crop yields and has improved the nutritional value of numerous crops, including corn, soybeans, and wheat.
[src:bran/agronomy] It has also resulted in the development of new types of plants.
[src:bran/agronomy] For example, a hybrid grain named triticale was produced by crossbreeding rye and wheat.
[src:bran/agronomy] Triticale contains more usable protein than does either rye or wheat.
[src:bran/agronomy] Agronomy has also been instrumental for fruit and vegetable production research.
[src:bran/agronomy] Furthermore, the application of plant breeding for turfgrass development has resulted in a reduction in the demand for fertilizer and water inputs (requirements), as well as turf-types with higher disease resistance.
[src:bran/agronomy] Agronomists use biotechnology to extend and expedite the development of desired characteristics.
[src:bran/agronomy] Biotechnology is often a laboratory activity requiring field testing of new crop varieties that are developed.
[src:bran/agronomy] In addition to increasing crop yields agronomic biotechnology is being applied increasingly for novel uses other than food.
[src:bran/agronomy] For example, oilseed is at present used mainly for margarine and other food oils, but it can be modified to produce fatty acids for detergents, substitute fuels and petrochemicals.
[src:bran/agronomy] Agronomists study sustainable ways to make soils more productive and profitable.
[src:bran/agronomy] They classify soils and analyze them to determine whether they contain nutrients vital for plant growth.
[src:bran/agronomy] Common macronutrients analyzed include compounds of nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, and sulfur.
[src:bran/agronomy] Soil is also assessed for several micronutrients, like zinc and boron.
[src:bran/agronomy] The percentage of organic matter, soil pH, and nutrient holding capacity (cation exchange capacity) are tested in a regional laboratory.
[src:bran/agronomy] Agronomists will interpret these laboratory reports and make recommendations to modify soil nutrients for optimal plant growth.
[src:bran/agronomy] Additionally, agronomists develop methods to preserve soil and decrease the effects of [erosion] by wind and water.
[src:bran/agronomy] For example, a technique known as contour plowing may be used to prevent soil erosion and conserve rainfall.
[src:bran/agronomy] Researchers of agronomy also seek ways to use the soil more effectively for solving other problems.
[src:bran/agronomy] Such problems include the disposal of human and animal manure, water pollution, and pesticide accumulation in the soil, as well as preserving the soil for future generations such as the burning of paddocks after crop production.
[src:bran/agronomy] Pasture management techniques include no-till farming, planting of soil-binding grasses along contours on steep slopes, and using contour drains of depths as much as 1 metre.
[src:bran/agronomy] Agroecology is the management of agricultural systems with an emphasis on ecological and environmental applications.
[src:bran/agronomy] This topic is associated closely with work for sustainable agriculture, organic farming, and alternative food systems and the development of alternative cropping systems.
[src:bran/agronomy] Theoretical production ecology is the quantitative study of the growth of crops.
[src:bran/agronomy] The plant is treated as a kind of biological factory, which processes light, carbon dioxide, water, and nutrients into harvestable products.
[src:bran/agronomy] The main parameters are temperature, sunlight, standing crop biomass, plant production distribution, and nutrient and water supply.
[src:bran/aleurone] The aleurone layer surrounds the endosperm tissue of grass seeds and is morphologically and biochemically distinct from it.
[src:bran/aleurone] Starchy endosperm cells are large, irregularly shaped cells and contain starch grains while aleurone cells are cuboidal in shape and contain aleurone grains.
[src:bran/aleurone] In most cultivated cereals (wheat species, rye, oats, rice and maize) the aleurone is single-layered, whereas barley has a multicellular aleurone layer.
[src:bran/aleurone] Thick primary cell walls enclose and protect the aleurone cells.
[src:bran/aleurone] The aleurone layer is important for both the developing seed and the mature plant.
[src:bran/aleurone] The aleurone tissue accumulates large quantities of oils and lipids that are useful during seed development.
[src:bran/aleurone] It is also a site of mineral storage and in some species, functions in seed dormancy.
[src:bran/aleurone] The aleurone may also express several pathogen-protective proteins including PR-4.
[src:bran/aleurone] Aleurone also serves as the most dietarily beneficial fraction in many brans.
[src:bran/aleurone] In addition, the aleurone tissue contains many protein-storing vacuoles known as protein bodies.
[src:bran/aleurone] In cereals with starchy endosperm, the aleurone contains about 30% of the kernel's proteins.
[src:bran/aleurone] In multicolored corn, anthocyanin pigments in the aleurone layer give the kernels a dark, bluish-black color.
[src:bran/aleurone] Aleurone proteins can have two different morphological features, homogenous and heterogeneous.
[src:bran/aleurone] The homogenous aleurone consists of similar protein bodies (e.g.
[src:bran/aleurone] *Phaseolus vulgaris*) while the heterogeneous aleurone consists of granules of different shapes and types of proteins covered with a membrane (e.g.
[src:bran/aleurone] The development of the aleurone layer involves several periclinal, and anticlinal cell divisions and several steps of genetic regulation.
[src:bran/aleurone] The *dek1* gene and *crinkly4 (cr4)* kinase both function as positive regulators of aleurone cell fate.
[src:bran/aleurone] The normal *dek1* gene is needed in order to receive and respond to positional cues that determine the fate of aleurone cells during development.
[src:bran/aleurone] Mutants of the *dek1* gene block the formation of aleurone and cause the cells to develop as starchy endosperm cells instead of aleurone cells.
[src:bran/aleurone] This causes the seed to lack an aleurone layer.
[src:bran/aleurone] This mutation is caused by the insertion of a *Mu* transposon into the *dek1* gene, causing it to function incorrectly.
[src:bran/aleurone] However, this transposon may sometimes remove itself from the gene, restoring the function of *dek1*.
[src:bran/aleurone] Experiments in this area have helped demonstrate that the cues that determine aleurone positioning are still present in the later stages of development, and the aleurone cells still respond to these cues.
[src:bran/aleurone] Similar to the *dek1* mutation, genes with a mutation in the *cr4* gene also cause a switch in the fate of aleurone cells.
[src:bran/aleurone] The *cr4* gene codes for a receptor kinase and so is involved in signal transduction pathways involving the fate of aleurone cells.
[src:bran/aleurone] Plants with a mutated *cr4* gene are shorter than normal and produce crinkled leaves.
[src:bran/aleurone] In addition, several hormones influence the development of the aleurone layer, including auxin, cytokinin, abscisic acid (ABA), and gibberellin (GA).
[src:bran/aleurone] Auxin and cytokinin play a role in the earlier stages of aleurone development.
[src:bran/aleurone] The maturation of aleurone is promoted by ABA while germination is promoted by GA.
[src:bran/aleurone] The aleurone layer performs a variety of functions to help maintain proper development of the seed.
[src:bran/aleurone] One example of this is maintaining a low pH in the apoplast.
[src:bran/aleurone] In cereals, the aleurone layer releases organic and phosphoric acids in order to keep the pH of the endosperm between a pH of 3.5 and 4.
[src:bran/aleurone] In barley, the aleurone layer also releases nitrite into the starchy endosperm and apoplast under anaerobic conditions.
[src:bran/aleurone] In addition, although the function is unclear, a certain class of hemoglobins is present in the outer layer of living cells including the aleurone tissue in barley and rice seeds.
[src:bran/aleurone] During seed germination, the plant embryo produces the hormone gibberellin which triggers the aleurone cells to release α-amylase for the hydrolysis of starch, proteases, and storage proteins into the endosperm.
[src:bran/aleurone] Evidence that G-proteins play a role in the gibberellin signaling events has been obtained.
[src:bran/aleurone] The breakdown of the starchy endosperm supplies sugars to drive the growth of roots and the acrospire.
[src:bran/aleurone] This release of amylase is considered to be the most important and sole function of the aleurone layer.
[src:bran/aleurone] This effect is inhibited by the plant hormone abscisic acid, which keeps the seed dormant.
[src:bran/aleurone] After completing this function, the aleurone cells in the developing seed undergo apoptosis.
[src:bran/aleurone] Experiments conducted in the 1960s confirmed that in order for the aleurone layer to secrete starch-degrading enzymes, the embryo must be present.
[src:bran/aleurone] Following removal of the embryo, starch-degrading enzymes were not released and no degradation of the starch tissue occurred.
[src:bran/aleurone] The gibberellin effect on the aleurone is used in brewing, specifically in the production of barley malt where treatment ensures that a batch of barley seeds will germinate evenly.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] Alkylresorcinols are relatively rare in nature and are reported to be found in fungi, bacteria, and some lower and higher plants.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] DB-2073 is an antibiotic isolated from the broth culture of *Pseudomonas* sp.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] They are also the main constituents of the outer shell of the cyst of *Azotobacter*.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] Among the plant sources, the shell oil of cashew nut (*Anacardium occidentale* L.) has the highest amount of ARs, which consists of 20% phenolic lipids.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] Moreover, ARs were found in the peels and pulp of peas (*Pisum sativum* L.), pulp and leaves of ginkgo (*Ginkgo biloba* L.), pulp and peels of mango (*Mangifera indica* L.), and in some cereals.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] In the case of cereals, the hyaline layer, inner pericarp, and testa showed the highest amounts of AR.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] The alkylresorcinols alkyl chain, present in cereals, ranges from 15 to 25 carbon atoms.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] ARs have been reported to be present in high amounts in rye, wheat, and triticale, and in low concentrations in barley, maize, oat, and millet, while no information is at present available for Khorasan wheat.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] They are most abundant in the bran fractions (2600-4100 μg/g; 0.1-0.3% of dry weight), whereas they are in trace amounts in strachy endosperm and germ.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] They can also be found in rice, though not in the edible parts of the rice plant.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] Their presence in the endosperm (the part of cereal grain that is used to make white flour), means that alkylresorcinols can be used as '**biomarkers**' for people who eat foods containing wholegrain wheat and rye, rather than cereal products based on white flour.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] Increasing evidence from human intervention trials suggests that they are the most promising biomarker of whole grain wheat and rye intake.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] Alkylresorcinol metabolites, 3,5-dihydroxybenzoic acid (DHBA) and 3,5-dihydroxyphenylpropionoic acid (DHPPA) were first identified in urine and can be quantified in urine and plasma, and may be an alternative, equivalent biomarker of whole grain wheat intake.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] The average intake of alkylresorcinols in the UK is around 11 mg/person/day, and in Sweden is around 20 mg/person/day.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] This varies widely depending on whether people normally consume wholegrain/wholemeal/brown bread, which is high in alkylresorcinols (300-1000 μg/g), or white wheat bread, which has very low concentrations of alkylresorcinols (<50 μg/g).
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] Recently, alkylresorcinols have been widely recognised as a biomarker for the presence of cereals in archaeological pottery.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] They were previously found in a well-preserved Bronze Age wooden container from Switzerland, and coarse ware vessels from a Roman cavalry barrack at Vindolanda.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] A study demonstrated that the survival of ARs is highly dependent on the cooking procedures and burial conditions.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] However, if recoverable, analysis of these phenolic lipids in archaeological contexts is valuable as it can help explain the uptake and spread of cereal processing of past communities in particular regions.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] In vitro studies have shown that alkylresorcinols may prevent cells turning cancerous, but that they do not have any effect on cells that are already cancerous.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] Alkylresorcinols also increase gamma-tocopherol levels in rats when fed in high amounts (0.2% of total diet and above).
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] The alkylresorcinols in *Grevillea banksii* and Grevillea 'Robyn Gordon' are responsible for contact dermatitis.
[src:bran/alkylresorcinols] Sorgoleone is a hydrophobic root exudate of *Sorghum bicolor*.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] These symptoms typically start in minutes to hours and then increase very rapidly to life-threatening levels.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Urgent medical treatment is required to prevent serious harm and death, even if the patient has used an epinephrine autoinjector or has taken other medications in response, and even if symptoms appear to be improving.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Common causes include allergies to insect bites and stings, allergies to foods—including nuts, peanuts, milk, fish, eggs; allergies to medications – including some antibiotics and non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs); or allergies to anaesthetics or latex.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Other causes can include physical exercise, and cases may also occur in some people due to escalating reactions to simple throat irritation or may also occur without an obvious reason.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The mast cell disease mastocytosis, along with the mast cell disorder mast cell activation syndrome are both capable of triggering anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The mechanism involves the release of inflammatory mediators in a rapidly escalating cascade from certain types of white blood cells triggered by either immunologic or non-immunologic mechanisms.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Diagnosis is based on the presenting symptoms and signs after exposure to a potential allergen or irritant.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The primary treatment of anaphylaxis is epinephrine injection into a muscle, intravenous fluids, then placing the person in a reclining position with feet elevated to help restore normal blood flow.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Additional doses of epinephrine may be required.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Other measures, such as antihistamines and steroids, are complementary.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Carrying an epinephrine autoinjector, commonly called an "epipen", and identification regarding the condition is recommended in people with a history of anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Immediately contacting ambulance / EMT services is strongly recommended, regardless of any on-site treatment.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Getting to a doctor or hospital as soon as possible is important, even if the condition appears to be getting better.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Worldwide, 0.05–2% of the population is estimated to experience anaphylaxis at some point in life.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Globally, as underreporting declined into the 2010s, the rate appeared to be increasing.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] It occurs most often in young people and females.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] About 99.7% of people hospitalized with anaphylaxis in the United States survive.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The word is derived from Ancient Greek: ἀνά, romanized: *ana*, lit.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] 'up', and Ancient Greek: φύλαξις, romanized: *phylaxis*, lit.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis typically presents many different symptoms over minutes or hours with an average onset of 5 to 30 minutes if exposure is intravenous and up to 2 hours if from eating food.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The most common areas affected include: skin (80–90%), respiratory (70%), gastrointestinal (30–45%), heart and vasculature (10–45%), and central nervous system (10–15%) with usually two or more being involved.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Symptoms typically include generalized hives, itchiness, flushing, or swelling (angioedema) of the affected tissues.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Those with angioedema may describe a burning sensation of the skin rather than itchiness.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Swelling of the tongue or throat occurs in up to about 20% of cases.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Other features may include a runny nose and swelling of the conjunctiva.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The skin may also be blue tinged because of a lack of oxygen.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Respiratory symptoms and signs that may be present include shortness of breath, wheezes, or stridor.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The wheezing is typically caused by spasms of the bronchial muscles while stridor is related to upper airway obstruction secondary to swelling.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Hoarseness, pain with swallowing, or a cough may also occur.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] While a fast heart rate caused by low blood pressure is more common, a Bezold–Jarisch reflex has been described in 10% of people, where a slow heart rate is associated with low blood pressure.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] A drop in blood pressure or shock (either distributive or cardiogenic) may cause the feeling of lightheadedness or loss of consciousness.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In rare cases, very low blood pressure may be the only sign of anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Coronary artery spasm may occur with subsequent myocardial infarction, dysrhythmia, or cardiac arrest.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Those with underlying coronary disease are at greater risk of cardiac effects from anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The coronary spasm is related to the presence of histamine-releasing cells in the heart.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Gastrointestinal symptoms may include severe crampy abdominal pain and vomiting.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] There may be confusion, a loss of bladder control or pelvic pain similar to that of uterine cramps.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Dilation of blood vessels around the brain may cause headaches.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] A feeling of anxiety or of "impending doom" has also been described.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis can occur in response to almost any foreign substance.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Common triggers include venom from insect bites or stings, foods, and medication.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Foods are the most common trigger in children and young adults, while medications and insect bites and stings are more common in older adults.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Less common causes include: physical factors, biological agents such as semen, latex, hormonal changes, food additives and colors, and topical medications.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Physical factors such as exercise (known as exercise-induced anaphylaxis) or temperature (either hot or cold) may also act as triggers through their direct effects on mast cells.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Events caused by exercise are frequently associated with cofactors such as the ingestion of certain foods or taking an NSAID.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis caused by a combination of exercise and consumption of certain foods is known as food-dependent exercise-induced anaphylaxis (FDEIA).
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease (AERD), alcohol is a common trigger.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] During anesthesia, neuromuscular blocking agents, antibiotics, and latex are the most common causes.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The cause remains unknown in 32–50% of cases, referred to as "idiopathic anaphylaxis." Six vaccines (MMR, varicella, influenza, hepatitis B, tetanus, meningococcal) are recognized as a cause for anaphylaxis, and HPV may cause anaphylaxis as well.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Many foods can trigger anaphylaxis; this may occur upon the first known ingestion.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Common triggering foods vary around the world due to cultural cuisine.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In Western cultures, ingestion of or exposure to peanuts, wheat, nuts, certain types of seafood like shellfish, milk, fruit and eggs are the most prevalent causes.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Sesame is common in the Middle East, while rice and chickpeas are frequently encountered as sources of anaphylaxis in Asia.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Severe cases are usually caused by ingesting the allergen, but some people experience a severe reaction upon contact.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] By age 16, 80% of children with anaphylaxis to milk or eggs and 20% who experience isolated anaphylaxis to peanuts can tolerate these foods.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Any type of alcohol, even in small amounts, can trigger anaphylaxis in people with AERD.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Any medication may potentially trigger anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The most common are β-lactam antibiotics (such as penicillin) followed by aspirin and NSAIDs.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Other antibiotics are implicated less frequently.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Anaphylactic reactions to NSAIDs are either agent specific or occur among those that are structurally similar, meaning that those who are allergic to one NSAID can typically tolerate a different one or a different group of NSAIDs.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Other relatively common causes include chemotherapy, vaccines, protamine and herbal preparations.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Some medications (vancomycin, morphine, x-ray contrast among others) cause anaphylaxis by directly triggering mast cell degranulation.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The frequency of a reaction to an agent partly depends on the frequency of its use and partly on its intrinsic properties.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis to penicillin or cephalosporins occurs only after it binds to proteins inside the body with some agents binding more easily than others.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis to penicillin occurs once in every 2,000 to 10,000 courses of treatment, with death occurring in fewer than one in every 50,000 courses of treatment.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis to aspirin and NSAIDs occurs in about one in every 50,000 persons.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] If someone reacts to penicillin, his or her risk of a reaction to cephalosporins is greater but still less than one in 1,000.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The old radiocontrast agents caused reactions in 1% of cases, while the newer, lower osmolar agents cause reactions in 0.04% of cases.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Avoidance of cephalosporins in those with penicillin allergy creates a significantly greater patient safety risk than the low probability of anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Venom from stinging or biting insects such as Hymenoptera (ants, bees, and wasps) or Triatominae (kissing bugs) may cause anaphylaxis in susceptible people.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Previous reactions that are anything more than a local reaction around the site of the sting, are a risk factor for future anaphylaxis; however, half of the fatalities have had no previous systemic reaction.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] People with atopic diseases such as asthma, eczema, or allergic rhinitis are at high risk of anaphylaxis from food, latex, and radiocontrast agents but not from injectable medications or stings.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] One study in children found that 60% had a history of previous atopic diseases, and of children who die from anaphylaxis, more than 90% have asthma.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Those with mastocytosis, mast cell activation syndrome (MCAS) or of a higher socioeconomic status are at increased risk.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis is a severe allergic reaction of rapid onset affecting many body systems.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] It is due to the release of inflammatory mediators and cytokines from mast cells and basophils, typically due to an immunologic reaction but sometimes with non-immunologic mechanisms.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Interleukin (IL)–4 and IL-13 are cytokines important in the initial generation of antibody and inflammatory cell responses to anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The vast majority of anaphylaxis is mediated by allergen-specific immunoglobulin E (IgE).
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In the immunologic mechanism, immunoglobulin E (IgE) binds to the antigen (the foreign material that provokes the allergic reaction).
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Antigen-bound IgE then activates FcεRI receptors on mast cells and basophils.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] This leads to the release of inflammatory mediators such as histamine.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] These mediators subsequently increase the contraction of bronchial smooth muscles, trigger vasodilation, increase the leakage of fluid from blood vessels, and compromise circulatory function.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Rarely, anaphylaxis may be triggered by immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Non-immunologic mechanisms involve substances that directly cause the degranulation of mast cells and basophils without ligating the high-affinity IgE receptor.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] These include agents such as contrast medium, opioids, temperature (hot or cold), and vibration.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Sulfites may cause reactions by both immunologic and non-immunologic mechanisms.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] This is a form of pseudoallergy and is commonly mediated by MRPRX2, a promiscuous receptor that interacts with many substances (especially drugs) to trigger mast cell degranulation without IgE.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] A form of anaphylaxis that has both IgE-dependent and non-IgE-dependent features has been observed as a consequence of some chemotherapy and monoclonal antibodies, manifesting alongside cytokine storm-like features.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis is diagnosed on the basis of a person's signs and symptoms.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Two or more of the following symptoms after a likely contact with an allergen: a.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Skin involvement may include: hives, itchiness, or a swollen tongue, among others.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Respiratory difficulties may include: shortness of breath, stridor, or low oxygen levels, among others.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Low blood pressure is defined as a greater than 30% decrease from a person's usual blood pressure.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In adults, a systolic blood pressure of less than 90 mmHg is often used.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] During an attack, blood tests for tryptase or histamine (released from mast cells) might be useful in diagnosing anaphylaxis due to insect stings or medications.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] However these tests are of limited use if the cause is food or if the person has a normal blood pressure, and they are not specific for the diagnosis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] To ensure that an elevated tryptase is not the result of hereditary alpha tryptasemia, the EAACI recommends repeating a tryptase level 24 hours after resolution of anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Additionally, a normal tryptase does not rule out anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] There are three main classifications of anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] **Biphasic anaphylaxis** is the recurrence of symptoms within 1–72 hours after resolution of an initial anaphylactic episode.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Estimates of incidence vary between less than 1% and up to 20% of cases.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The recurrence typically occurs within 8 hours.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] It is managed in the same manner as anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] **Anaphylactoid reaction**, **non-immune anaphylaxis**, or **pseudoanaphylaxis**, is a type of anaphylaxis that does not involve an allergic reaction but is due to direct mast cell degranulation.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Non-immune anaphylaxis is the current term, as of 2018, used by the World Allergy Organization with some recommending that the old terminology, "anaphylactoid", no longer be used.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Allergy testing may help in determining the trigger.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Skin allergy testing is available for certain foods and venoms.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Blood testing for specific IgE can be useful to confirm milk, egg, peanut, tree nut, and fish allergies.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Skin testing is available to confirm penicillin allergies, but is not available for other medications.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Non-immune forms of anaphylaxis can only be determined by history or exposure to the allergen in question, and not by skin or blood testing.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] It can sometimes be difficult to distinguish anaphylaxis from asthma, syncope, and panic attacks.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Asthma however typically does not entail itching or gastrointestinal symptoms, syncope presents with pallor rather than a rash, and a panic attack may have flushing but does not have hives.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Other conditions that may present similarly include: scrombroidosis and anisakiasis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In a person who died from anaphylaxis, autopsy may show an "empty heart" attributed to reduced venous return from vasodilation and redistribution of intravascular volume from the central to the peripheral compartment.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Other signs are laryngeal edema, eosinophilia in lungs, heart and tissues, and evidence of myocardial hypoperfusion.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Laboratory findings could detect increased levels of serum tryptase, an increase in total and specific IgE serum levels.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Avoidance of the trigger of anaphylaxis is recommended.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In cases where this may not be possible, desensitization may be an option.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Immunotherapy with Hymenoptera venoms is effective at desensitizing 80–90% of adults and 98% of children against allergies to bees, wasps, hornets, yellowjackets, and fire ants.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Oral immunotherapy may be effective at desensitizing some people to certain food including milk, eggs, nuts and peanuts; however, adverse effects are common.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] For example, many people develop an itchy throat, cough, or lip swelling during immunotherapy.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Desensitization is also possible for many medications, however it is usually advised that most people simply avoid the agent in question.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In those who react to latex it may be important to avoid cross-reactive foods such as avocados, bananas, and potatoes among others.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Premedications with antihistamines or glucocorticoids does not prevent anaphylaxis, but may be used in specific circumstances, such as rush aeroallergen desensitization or in certain chemotherapy regimens.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis is a medical emergency that may require resuscitation measures such as airway management, supplemental oxygen, large volumes of intravenous fluids, and close monitoring.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Passive leg raise may also be helpful in the emergency management.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Administration of intravenous fluid bolus and epinephrine is the treatment of choice with antihistamines used as adjuncts.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] A period of in-hospital observation for between 2 and 24 hours is recommended for people once they have returned to normal due to concerns of biphasic anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Epinephrine (adrenaline) (1:1000) is the primary treatment for anaphylaxis with no absolute contraindication to its use.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] It is recommended that an epinephrine solution be given intramuscularly into the mid anterolateral thigh as soon as the diagnosis is suspected.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The injection may be repeated every 5 to 15 minutes if there is insufficient response.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] A second dose is needed in 16–35% of episodes with more than two doses rarely required.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The intramuscular route is preferred over subcutaneous administration because the latter may have delayed absorption.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] It is recommended that after diagnosis and treatment of anaphylaxis, the patient should be kept under observation in an appropriate clinical setting until symptoms have fully resolved.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Minor adverse effects from epinephrine include tremors, anxiety, headaches, and palpitations.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] People on β-blockers may be resistant to the effects of epinephrine, but this is less of an issue with "cardioselective" β1-blockers.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In this situation, if epinephrine is not effective, intravenous glucagon can be administered, which has a mechanism of action independent of β-receptors.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] If necessary, it can also be given intravenously using a dilute epinephrine solution.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Intravenous epinephrine, however, has been associated both with dysrhythmia and myocardial infarction.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Epinephrine autoinjectors used for self-administration typically come in two doses, one for adults or children who weigh more than 25 kg and one for children who weigh 10 to 25 kg.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Most recently, the FDA has approved an intranasal form of epinephrine under the brand name Neffy, on the basis of its ability to attain levels of epinephrine in people that are believed to be protective against anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] There are currently no clinical data on its effectiveness.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Delayed administration of epinephrine in anaphylaxis is associated with increased rates of hospitalization and mortality.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Antihistamines (both H1 and H2), while commonly used and assumed effective based on theoretical reasoning, are poorly supported by evidence.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] A 2007 Cochrane review did not find any good-quality studies upon which to base recommendations and they are not believed to affect airway edema or spasm.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Corticosteroids are unlikely to make a difference in the current episode of anaphylaxis, but may be used in the hope of decreasing the risk of biphasic anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Their prophylactic effectiveness in these situations is uncertain.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Nebulized salbutamol may be effective for bronchospasm that does not resolve with epinephrine.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Methylene blue has been used in those not responsive to other measures due to its presumed effect of relaxing smooth muscle.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] People prone to anaphylaxis are advised to have an allergy action plan.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Parents are advised to inform schools of their children's allergies and what to do in case of an anaphylactic emergency.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The action plan usually includes use of epinephrine autoinjectors, the recommendation to wear a medical alert bracelet, and counseling on avoidance of triggers.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Immunotherapy is available for certain triggers to prevent future episodes of anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] A multi-year course of subcutaneous desensitization has been found effective against stinging insects, while oral desensitization is effective for many foods.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In those in whom the cause is known and prompt treatment is available, the prognosis is good.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Even if the cause is unknown, if appropriate preventive medication is available, the prognosis is generally good.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Usually, death occurs due to either respiratory failure (typically involving asphyxia) or cardiovascular complications, such as cardiovascular shock, with 0.7–20% of cases causing death.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] There have been cases of death occurring within minutes.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Outcomes in those with exercise-induced anaphylaxis are typically good, with fewer and less severe episodes as people get older.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The number of people who get anaphylaxis is 4–100 per 100,000 persons per year, with a lifetime risk of 0.05–2%.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] About 30% of affected people get more than one attack.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Exercise-induced anaphylaxis affects about 1 in 2000 young people.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Rates appear to be increasing: the numbers in the 1980s were approximately 20 per 100,000 per year, while in the 1990s, it was 50 per 100,000 per year.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The increase appears to be primarily for food-induced anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The risk is greatest in young people and females.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis leads to as many as 500–1,000 deaths per year (2.7 per million) in the United States, 20 deaths per year in the United Kingdom (0.33 per million), and 15 deaths per year in Australia (0.64 per million).
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Another estimate from the United States puts the death rate at 0.7 per million.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Mortality rates have decreased between the 1970s and 2000s.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In Australia, death from food-induced anaphylaxis occur primarily in women while deaths due to insect bites primarily occur in males.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Death from anaphylaxis is most commonly triggered by medications.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The conditions of anaphylaxis have been known since ancient times.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] French physician François Magendie had described how rabbits were killed by repeated injections of egg albumin in 1839.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] However, the phenomenon was discovered by two French physiologists Charles Richet and Paul Portier.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In 1901, Albert I, Prince of Monaco requested Richet and Portier join him on a scientific expedition around the French coast of the Atlantic Ocean, specifically to study on the toxin produced by cnidarians (like jellyfish and sea anemones).
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Richet and Portier boarded Albert's ship *Princesse Alice II* for ocean exploration to make collections of the marine animals.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Richet and Portier extracted a toxin called hypnotoxin from their collection of jellyfish (but the real source was later identified as Portuguese man o' war) and sea anemone (*Actinia sulcata*).
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In their first experiment on the ship, they injected a dog with the toxin in an attempt to immunise the dog, which instead developed a severe reaction (hypersensitivity).
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In 1902, they repeated the injections in their laboratory and found that dogs normally tolerated the toxin at the first injection, but on re-exposure, three weeks later with the same dose, they always developed fatal shock.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] They also found that the effect was not related to the doses of toxin used, as even small amounts in secondary injections were lethal.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Thus, instead of inducing tolerance (prophylaxis), which they expected, they discovered effects of the toxin as deadly.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] In 1902, Richet introduced the term *aphylaxis* to describe the condition of lack of protection.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] He later changed the term to *anaphylaxis* on the grounds of euphony.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The term is from the Greek ἀνά-, *ana-*, meaning "against", and φύλαξις, *phylaxis*, meaning "protection".
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] On 15 February 1902, Richet and Portier jointly presented their findings before the *Societé de Biologie* in Paris.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] The moment is regarded as the birth of allergy (the term invented by Clemens von Pirquet in 1906) study (allergology).
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Richet continued to study the phenomenon and was eventually awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his work on anaphylaxis in 1913.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] There are ongoing efforts to develop sublingual epinephrine to treat anaphylaxis.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Trials of sublingual epinephrine, currently called AQST-108 (dipivefrin) and sponsored by Aquestive Therapeutics, are in phase 1 trials as of December 2021.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Subcutaneous injection of the anti-IgE antibody omalizumab is being studied as a method of preventing recurrence, but it is not yet recommended.
[src:bran/anaphylaxis] Omalizumab-associated anaphylaxis has been observed in less than 0.1% of patients treated for moderate to severe persistent allergic asthma using subcutaneous omalizumab injections.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Animal wellbeing is highly dependent on feed that reflects a well balanced nutrition.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Some modern agricultural practices, such as fattening cows on grains or in feed lots, have detrimental effects on the environment and animals.
[src:bran/animal-feed] For example, increased corn or other grain in feed for cows, makes their microbiomes more acidic weakening their immune systems and making cows a more likely vector for *E. coli*, while other feeding practices can improve animal impacts.
[src:bran/animal-feed] For example, feeding cows certain kinds of seaweed, reduces their production of methane, reducing the greenhouse gases from meat production.
[src:bran/animal-feed] When an environmental crisis strikes farmers or herders, such as a drought or extreme weather driven by climate change, farmers often have to shift to more expensive manufactured animal feed, which can negatively effect their economic viability.
[src:bran/animal-feed] For example, a 2017 drought in Senegal reduced the availability of grazing lands leading to skyrocketing demand and prices for manufactured animal feed, causing farmers to sell large portions of their herds.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Additionally agriculture for producing animal feed puts pressure on land use: feed crops need land that otherwise might be used for human food and can be one of the driving factors for deforestation, soil degradation and climate change.
[src:bran/animal-feed] "Fodder" refers particularly to foods or forages given to the animals (including plants cut and carried to them), rather than that which they forage for themselves.
[src:bran/animal-feed] It includes hay, straw, silage, compressed and pelleted feeds, oils and mixed rations, and sprouted grains and legumes.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Grass and crop residues are the most important source of animal feed globally.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Grains account for 11% of the total dry matter consume by livestock at global level and oilseed crops by-products such as soybean cakes account for 5%.
[src:bran/animal-feed] The amount of grain used to produce the same unit of meat varies substantially between species and production systems.
[src:bran/animal-feed] According to FAO, ruminants require an average of 2.8 kg of grains to produce 1 kg of meat while monogastrics require 3.2.
[src:bran/animal-feed] These figures vary between 0.1 for extensive ruminant systems to 9.4 in beef feedlots, and from 0.1 in backyard chicken production to 4 in industrial pig production.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Farmed fish can also be fed on grain and use even less than poultry.
[src:bran/animal-feed] The two most important feed grains are maize and soybean, and the United States is by far the largest exporter of both, averaging about half of the global maize trade and 40% of the global soya trade in the years leading up the 2012 drought.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Other feed grains include wheat, oats, barley, and rice, among many others.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Traditional sources of animal feed include household food scraps and the byproducts of food processing industries such as milling and brewing.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Material remaining from milling oil crops like peanuts, soy, and corn are important sources of fodder.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Scraps fed to pigs are called slop, and those fed to chicken are called chicken scratch.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Brewer's spent grain is a byproduct of beer making that is widely used as animal feed.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Compound feed is fodder that is blended from various raw materials and additives.
[src:bran/animal-feed] These blends are formulated according to the specific requirements of the target animal.
[src:bran/animal-feed] They are manufactured by feed compounders as *meal type*, *pellets* or *crumbles*.
[src:bran/animal-feed] The main ingredients used in commercially prepared feed are the feed grains, which include corn, soybeans, sorghum, oats, and barley.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Compound feed may also include premixes, which may also be sold separately.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Premixes are composed of microingredients such as vitamins, minerals, chemical preservatives, antibiotics, fermentation products, and other ingredients that are purchased from premix companies, usually in sacked form, for blending into commercial rations.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Because of the availability of these products, farmers who use their own grain can formulate their own rations and be assured that their animals are getting the recommended levels of minerals and vitamins, although they are still subject to the Veterinary Feed Directive.
[src:bran/animal-feed] According to the American Feed Industry Association, as much as $20 billion worth of feed ingredients are purchased each year.
[src:bran/animal-feed] These products range from grain mixes to orange rinds and beet pulps.
[src:bran/animal-feed] The feed industry is one of the most competitive businesses in the agricultural sector and is by far the largest purchaser of U.S. corn, feed grains, and soybean meal.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Tens of thousands of farmers with feed mills on their own farms are able to compete with huge conglomerates with national distribution.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Feed crops generated $23.2 billion in cash receipts on U.S. farms in 2001.
[src:bran/animal-feed] At the same time, farmers spent a total of $24.5 billion on feed that year.
[src:bran/animal-feed] With progressing climate change and reoccurring droughts, extensive rangeland agriculture increasingly suffers of forage shortage.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Innovative approaches to substitute forage include the harvesting and processing of shrubs into animal feed.
[src:bran/animal-feed] This has been extensively researched and applied in Namibia, using waste biomass resulting from woody encroachment.
[src:bran/animal-feed] In 2011, around 734.5 million tons of feed were produced annually around the world.
[src:bran/animal-feed] The US Animal Drug Availability Act 1996, passed during the Clinton era, was the first attempt in that country to regulate the use of medicated feed.
[src:bran/animal-feed] In 1997, in response to outbreaks of Bovine spongiform encephalopathy, commonly known as mad cow disease, the United States and Canada banned a range of animal tissues from cattle feed.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Feed bans in United States (2009) Canada (2007) expanded on this, prohibiting the use of potentially infectious tissue in all animal and pet food and fertilizers.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Forage is a plant material (mainly plant leaves and stems) eaten by grazing livestock.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Historically, the term *forage* has meant only plants eaten by the animals directly as pasture, crop residue, or immature cereal crops, but it is also used more loosely to include similar plants cut for fodder and carried to the animals, especially as hay or silage.
[src:bran/animal-feed] While the term *forage* has a broad definition, the term *forage crop* is used to define crops, annual or biennial, which are grown to be utilized by grazing or harvesting as a whole crop.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Feed manufacturing refers to the process of producing animal feed from raw agricultural products.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Fodder produced by manufacturing is formulated to meet specific animal nutrition requirements for different species of animals at different life stages.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Create a formula: Nutritionists work side by side with scientists to formulate nutritionally sound and balanced diets for livestock, poultry, aquaculture and pets.
[src:bran/animal-feed] This is a complex process, as every species has different nutritional requirements.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Mix ingredients: Once the formula is determined, the mill mixes the ingredients to create a finished product.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Package and label: Manufacturers determine the best way to ship the product.
[src:bran/animal-feed] If it is prepared for retail, it will be "bagged and tagged," or placed into a bag with a label that includes the product's purpose, ingredients and instructions.
[src:bran/animal-feed] If the product is prepared for commercial use, it will be shipped in bulk.
[src:bran/animal-feed] In agriculture today, the nutritional needs of farm animals are well understood and may be satisfied through natural forage and fodder alone, or augmented by direct supplementation of nutrients in concentrated, controlled form.
[src:bran/animal-feed] The nutritional quality of feed is influenced not only by the nutrient content, but also by many other factors such as feed presentation, hygiene, digestibility, and effect on intestinal health.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Feed additives provide a mechanism through which these nutrient deficiencies can be resolved, improving animal rate of growth, health, and well-being.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Many farm animals have a diet largely consisting of grain-based ingredients because of the higher costs of quality feed.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Chelates in animal feed is jargon for metalloorganic compounds added to animal feed.
[src:bran/animal-feed] The compounds provide sources of various metals that improve the health or marketability of the animal.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Typical metal salts are derived from cobalt, copper, iron, manganese, and zinc.
[src:bran/animal-feed] The objective of supplementation with trace minerals is to avoid a variety of deficiency diseases.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Trace minerals carry out key functions in relation to many metabolic processes, most notably as cofactors for enzymes and hormones, and are essential for optimum health, growth and productivity.
[src:bran/animal-feed] For example, supplementary minerals help ensure good growth, bone development, feathering in birds, hoof, skin and hair quality in mammals, enzyme structure and functions, and appetite.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Deficiency of trace minerals affects many metabolic processes and so may be manifested by different symptoms, such as poor growth and appetite, reproductive failures, impaired immune responses, and general ill-thrift.
[src:bran/animal-feed] From the 1950s to the 1990s most trace mineral supplementation of animal diets was in the form of inorganic minerals, and these largely eradicated associated deficiency diseases in farm animals.
[src:bran/animal-feed] The role in fertility and reproductive diseases of dairy cattle highlights that organic forms of Zn are retained better than inorganic sources and so may provide greater benefit in disease prevention, notably mastitis and lameness.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Animals are thought to better absorb, digest, and use mineral chelates than inorganic minerals or simple salts.
[src:bran/animal-feed] In theory lower concentrations of these minerals can be used in animal feeds.
[src:bran/animal-feed] In addition, animals fed chelated sources of essential trace minerals excrete lower amounts in their faeces, and so there is less environmental contamination.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Insects may be able to supplement livestock feed, as they can transform low-value organic waste into nutritious products.
[src:bran/animal-feed] On the other hand, insect production presents a number of unresolved environmental challenges.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Insect farms require constant heating at around 30 °C, resulting in high energy consumption.
[src:bran/animal-feed] According to a study commissioned by the UK government, insects emit 5 to 13 times more greenhouse gases than soybean meal.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Their rearing consumes more water per kilogram than pork, chicken or beef, and most insects are fed on high-quality agricultural by-products rather than waste, putting them in direct competition with existing animal feed.
[src:bran/animal-feed] The issue of local biodiversity risk if insects escape into the wild has also been raised.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Soybean meal is used in food and animal feeds, principally as a protein supplement, but also as a source of metabolizable energy.
[src:bran/animal-feed] 60 lbs. or 27.2 kg) of soybeans yields 48 lbs.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Most soybean meal is defatted, produced as a co-product of soybean oil extraction.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Some, but not all, soybean meal contains ground soybean hulls.
[src:bran/animal-feed] Soybean meal is heat-treated during production, to denature the trypsin inhibitors of soybeans, which would otherwise interfere with protein digestion.
[src:bran/awb-limited] The AWB was founded in 1939 to regulate the wheat market after the excesses of the Great Depression.
[src:bran/awb-limited] This type of arrangement was not unique to Australia, as the Canadian Wheat Board was created in 1935 in a similar fashion (but its history dates back to an earlier wheat marketing board created during World War I, and also includes the experience of cooperative wheat pools during the 1920s).
[src:bran/awb-limited] For much of its early history, it was a government-run and owned company.
[src:bran/awb-limited] In July 1999, it was restructured as a private company.
[src:bran/awb-limited] It offered "class A" shares to those who met its definition of growers and who had the ability to elect the majority of its board and chairperson, and from August 2001, 'class B' were publicly traded on the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:bran/awb-limited] In 2008, constitutional amendments were passed.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Despite resistance from several wheat lobbies and industry groups, it consolidated ownership of AWB into one type of share, giving growers no special consideration.
[src:bran/awb-limited] This change was proposed by the AWB management as necessarily to having a simpler, lower-risk business model.
[src:bran/awb-limited] After privatisation, AWB grew to incorporate a number of subsidiaries to diversify its income away from its wheat exports.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Its subsidiary businesses include GrainFlow to manage collection of grain from farmers to ports, companies to ship the grain overseas to customers, and Landmark rural services.
[src:bran/awb-limited] AWB Limited was a holding company owning a number of subsidiaries.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Its shares were freely traded on the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:bran/awb-limited] AWB Limited had a number of subsidiaries.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Some of these subsidiaries existed due to legislative requirements relating to the operation of the single desk; others exist for the purpose of controlling credit risk.
[src:bran/awb-limited] AWB announced a new strategy in 2009 to simplify and de-risk the business.
[src:bran/awb-limited] This resulted in the divestment of the financial services loan book to the ANZ Bank in December 2009.
[src:bran/awb-limited] In March 2010, AWB announced the signing of a memorandum of understanding to sell the Geneva business and to joint venture the local grain trading business.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Previously a low profile organisation, the AWB made headlines in late 2005 when it was alleged that it had knowingly paid kickbacks to the Iraq Government, in violation of United Nations sanctions and Australian law.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Following the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990, the United Nations had imposed a financial and trade embargo on Iraq.
[src:bran/awb-limited] However, after facing criticism over the humanitarian impacts of the sanctions, the UN from 1995 until late 2003 allowed Iraq to trade oil on the world market in exchange for food, medicine and other humanitarian needs.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Despite this, at the insistence of the Iraq government of dictator Saddam Hussein, the AWB agreed to pay "transportation fees" of around $A$290 million.
[src:bran/awb-limited] This money was paid to a Jordanian transportation company, Alia.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Alia kept a small percentage of the fees, and paid the remainder onto Saddam's government.
[src:bran/awb-limited] This breached the sanctions placed on the Iraqi regime.
[src:bran/awb-limited] The government-sanctioned Cole Inquiry into the company's role in the scandal has been completed and was tabled by Attorney-General Philip Ruddock on 27 November 2006.
[src:bran/awb-limited] The report found that, from mid-1999, AWB had knowingly entered into an arrangement that involved paying kickbacks to the Iraqi government, in order to retain its business.
[src:bran/awb-limited] The Inquiry recommended that 12 people be investigated for possible criminal and corporations offences over the scandal.
[src:bran/awb-limited] At the height of the investigation, the single-desk arrangement from which AWB benefits came under criticism.
[src:bran/awb-limited] In 2006, the Australian Grain Exporters Association asked the Government to remove AWB's monopoly export powers.
[src:bran/awb-limited] The oil-for-wheat scandal cast doubt among some grain exporters over the trust placed in the company, especially as they lost the ability to export to Iraq during the length of the Cole Inquiry, losing one of their biggest markets.
[src:bran/awb-limited] The scandal resulted in international condemnation and litigation.
[src:bran/awb-limited] On 11 July 2006, North American farmers claimed $1 billion in damages from AWB at Washington DC, alleging the Australian wheat exporter used bribery and other corrupt activities to corner grain markets.
[src:bran/awb-limited] The growers claimed that AWB used the same techniques to secure grain sales in other markets in Asia and other countries in the Middle East.
[src:bran/awb-limited] The lawsuit was dismissed in March 2007.
[src:bran/awb-limited] In August 2009, the Australian Federal Police dropped their investigation into any criminal actions undertaken by AWB and others in this matter.
[src:bran/awb-limited] This decision came after Paul Hastings QC declared the prospect of convictions was limited and "not in the public interest".
[src:bran/awb-limited] The Australian Securities & Investments Commission then proceeded with several civil cases against six former directors and officers of AWB.
[src:bran/awb-limited] AWB's former managing director Andrew Lindberg and former chief financial officer Paul Ingleby were ultimately fined and banned from managing a company for one year.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Former chairman Trevor Flugge was also fined, and banned from managing a company for five years.
[src:bran/awb-limited] A civil suit brought by shareholders of AWB was settled out of court for $39.5 million in February 2010.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Australia's government has distanced itself from the payments to Saddam Hussein's regime, given Australia's contribution to military action against Hussein in the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Andrew Lindberg resigned as managing director on 9 February 2006 and from the board of directors on 22 February 2006 under intense public and media pressure.
[src:bran/awb-limited] In the years immediately following the Cole Inquiry, AWB continued to be dogged by bad performance.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Following the publication of the Cole Inquiry, a new management team was installed under the leadership of Gordon Davis who was recruited from Orica in August 2006.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Davis successfully reformed the constitution and the shareholder structure to consolidate into 1 class of shareholder.
[src:bran/awb-limited] This new management team has not been entirely without controversy.
[src:bran/awb-limited] On 26 April 2007, Yahoo News reported that AWB also breached US sanctions on Iran.
[src:bran/awb-limited] These sanctions prohibit American citizens and companies using American currency from trading with Iran.
[src:bran/awb-limited] In 2006, AWB's US subsidiary attempted to pay an Iranian transport company approximately $1 million, in clear breach of the US sanctions.
[src:bran/awb-limited] In 2009, the company faced difficulties in another new market, when it was forced to recapitalise the balance sheet after the company produced significant losses from the expansion of trading activities into Brazil under Davis.
[src:bran/awb-limited] Despite making a small profit in 2009, in March 2010, the company announced a profit downgrade from domestic trading activities.
[src:bran/awb-limited] In May 2010, it reported a half-year loss of $64.8 million, which it claimed due to the cost of settling the shareholder class action for $39.5m, and a loss of $65.4m on restructuring costs associated with its sale of the Landmark Financial Services loan and deposit books.
[src:bran/awb-limited] In July 2010, AWB entered into an agreement to merge with GrainCorp.
[src:bran/awb-limited] This did not proceed, after Agrium made a successful takeover offer that was completed in December 2010, with the company delisted from the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:bran/awb-limited] In 2011, Cargill acquired the AWB Commodity Management business from Agrium.
[src:bran/bran] Bran is present in cereal grain, including rice, corn (maize), wheat, oats, barley, rye, and millet.
[src:bran/bran] Bran is not the same as chaff, which is a coarser, scaly material surrounding the grain and is indigestible by humans.
[src:bran/bran] Bran is particularly rich in dietary fiber and essential fatty acids, and contains significant quantities of starch, protein, vitamins, and dietary minerals.
[src:bran/bran] It is also a source of phytic acid, an antinutrient that prevents nutrient absorption.
[src:bran/bran] The high oil content of bran makes it subject to rancidification, one of the reasons that it is often separated from the grain before storage or further processing.
[src:bran/bran] Bran is often heat-treated to increase its shelf life.
[src:bran/bran] Rice bran is a byproduct of the rice-milling process (the conversion of brown rice to white rice), and it contains various antioxidants.
[src:bran/bran] A major rice bran fraction contains 12%–13% oil and highly unsaponifiable components (4.3%).
[src:bran/bran] This fraction contains tocotrienols (a form of vitamin E), gamma-oryzanol, and beta-sitosterol; all these constituents may contribute to the lowering of the plasma levels of the various parameters of the lipid profile.
[src:bran/bran] Rice bran also contains a high level of dietary fiber (beta-glucan, pectin, and gum).
[src:bran/bran] It also contains ferulic acid, which is also a component of the structure of nonlignified cell walls.
[src:bran/bran] Some research suggests, however, that inorganic arsenic is present at some level in rice bran.
[src:bran/bran] One study found the levels to be 20% higher than in contaminated drinking water.
[src:bran/bran] Bran is often used to enrich breads (notably muffins) and breakfast cereals, especially for the benefit of those wishing to increase their intake of dietary fiber.
[src:bran/bran] Bran may also be used for pickling (*nukazuke*) as in the *tsukemono* of Japan, as well as in the production of East Asian black vinegars.
[src:bran/bran] Rice bran in particular finds many uses in Japan, where it is known as *nuka* (糠; ぬか).
[src:bran/bran] Besides using it for pickling, Japanese people add it to the water when boiling bamboo shoots, and use it for dish washing.
[src:bran/bran] In Kitakyushu City, it is called *jinda* and used for stewing fish, such as sardines.
[src:bran/bran] Wheat bran is useful as feed for poultry and other livestock, as part of a balanced ration with other inputs.
[src:bran/bran] Wheatings, a milling byproduct comprising mostly bran with some pieces of endosperm also left over, are included in this category.
[src:bran/bran] Bran oil may be also extracted for use by itself for industrial purposes (such as in the paint industry), or as a cooking oil, such as rice bran oil.
[src:bran/bran] Bran was found to be the most successful slug deterrent by BBC's TV programme *Gardeners' World*.
[src:bran/bran] It is a common substrate and food source used for feeder insects, such as mealworms and waxworms.
[src:bran/bran] Wheat bran has also been used for tanning leather since at least the 16th century.
[src:bran/bran] As with cereal fibers and whole grain consumption, bran is under preliminary research for the potential to improve nutrition and affect chronic diseases.
[src:bran/bran] The authors recommended that heat treatment should be sufficient to achieve selective lipase inactivation, but not so much as to render the polar lipids oxidizable upon prolonged storage.
